summary.seg: The first thing a reader notes about Trinity College MS O.1.77 is its small size. This tiny medical handbook measures 105 x 70 mm (4.13 x 2.76 in), which makes it truly portable in a pocket or a pouch, hanging from the belt. Most of the manuscript is written on paper. Here the paper was likely folded into sixteen sections to produce a 'sextodecimo' (also known as '16mo' and 'sixteenmo'). Paper manuscripts are divided into sizes based on how many times the paper had to be folded. Folio was folded a single time, producing a large and expensive book equivalent of a modern 'coffee-table book'. Quarto and octavo were the two most popular sizes, in which the paper was folded to produce four or eight leaves respectively.

The contents of the manuscript are typical for the mid- to late fifteenth century. It contains texts for making diagnoses based on the colour of the patient's urine and the humoral disposition of the patient based on the position of the zodiac. There are texts for making purgative and laxative remedies and no fewer than three texts on the plague, all different versions of a treatise by a fourteenth-century physician John of Burgundy, who wrote the most common plague tract in medieval England and Scotland. The fifteenth century is known as a high time for astrological medicine and alcohol-based medicaments – both of which are well represented in Trinity College MS O.1.77.

The manuscript has attracted scholarly interest due to its connections to commercial copying of medical manuscripts in London. The early part of collection consists of an anthology of medical texts that is found in nearly identical order in six manuscripts, known as the Voigts-Sloane Sibling Group (named after Linda Voigts, who first identified them in 1990, and the Sloane Collection in the British Library, where many of the manuscripts are located). The texts in common likely constituted a set group that was used as an exemplar in a workshop engaged in commercial book production. Two other Voigts-Sloane Siblings are also pocket-sized - London, British Library, Sloane MS 3566 and Boston, Countway Library of Medicine, Ballard MS 19 - indicating the existence of a market for these texts in a portable format.

However, MS O.1.77 differs from its two pocket-sized siblings by containing additional texts. These include a much longer astrological section and two texts for alcohol-based treatments: an extract from De Vinis, a book on medicinal properties of wines by Arnaldus de Villa Nova (d. 1311) and the Book of Quintessence by John of Rupescissa (d. c. 1365/1370), a text which promises to give instructions on distilling the mysterious fifth element, which has truly remarkable healing qualities (however, the resulting substance seems to be a pure form of alcohol). The latter is copied on parchment rather than paper, though the poor quality suggests that it comprises 'off-cuts', small pieces left over from preparing parchment for book, which were often cheaper than paper. Altogether, these texts enhanced the standard anthology by providing what was considered at the time to be cutting-edge medical treatments. That the book was put to practical use is evidenced by the concentration of wear and tear around pages that advised about diagnosis, such as the coloured urine flasks on ff. 24v-29v.

msItem.title: Note on weights and measures in Middle English

note.p:
Full transcription of the text on weights and measures in Middle English on f. [ii] recto:
Þo wiȝtes is straunge and harde to knowe y wole titil hem here a povnde is þus writen lj.j. Halfe a povnde þus .lj.ß. Oþer þus lj.dj. A . quartron þus .quart.j. An vnce þus .℥. halfe an vnce þus ℥ß or þus ℥dj , A drame þus ʒj , half a drame . ʒß. or þus. ʒdj. , A scripule þus .℈j. half a scripule þus .℈ß. or þus .℈ dj. A scripule weieþ a peny . and iije scripules ben a drame . and viij drames a vnce . and xvj vnces make a povnde , And an handful is writen þus mj. and halfe an handful þus . mß. or þus .mdj. etc
The scribe writes the 'ounce' siglum in a style that resembles a Hindu-Arabic '2' more than the traditional form.

Voigts noted similar versions of this text in:
Cambridge, Emmanuel College, MS 70, f. 149v
London, British Library, MS Additional 30338, f. 11r
London, British Library, MS Sloane 3171, ff. 1v-2r
London, Medical Society, MS 131, f. 3r

[iii] recto in a morter and putte somme of þe suger with al and after for ellis it wille not be beten and after þat . put al in a vessel and menge it together and bete it to pouder til it be sotel . and take ha di sponeful . or a sponeful at ones þerof by day time . or nyȝt tyme as þe semeþ nede etc

msItem.title: Treatise on the planets
msItem.incipit: 104v Quicumque cursum lune scire desiderat ; sciat primo quomodo sol per signa radit . Vnde Tholomeus . Inter has septem planetas ; sol quasi rex existit . quia locatur in medio . tres videlicet planetam habet supra se .6. saturnum, iouis, et martem . et tres alias habet sub se positas . videlicet Venerem . mercurium et lunam . et est tanquam fons luminis et colorem . cuncta illuminat et calefacit super se posita et sub se ordinata.
msItem.explicit: 109r Taurus . virgo . capricornus . terra frigida rea australia meridionale malen et sicca colica , Geminius . libra . aquarius calidi et humidi aeria . occidentalia . sanguinea

note.p: Attributed to Robert Grosseteste ('Hec Lincolensis') in the rubric.

Text is probably defective, with a quire probably missing between ff. 105v and f. 106r, the boundary between the present Quires 13 and 14. The catchwords at the bottom of f. 105v ('a sole vte folium') do not match the opening words of f. 106r, 'in kalendario', and the medieval alphanumeric leaf signatures are disrupted at the boundary between Quires 13 and 14; the first (cancelled) sequence jumps from 'S' (Quire 13) to 'V' (Quire 14) omitting 'T', and the second sequence jumps from 'n' (Quire 13) to 'p' (Quire 14) omitting 'o'.

Other similar texts: Erfurt, Universitätsbibliothek Erfurt, Dep. Erf., CA 4° 385, ff. 159r-162r, and London, Wellcome Library, MS 537, ff. 318v-319v, the Wellcome manuscript and Trinity MS O.1.77 diverge at the end of Trinity MS O.1.77 f. 105v.

msItem.title: Treatise on the planets
msItem.incipit: 109r CVm luna fuerit in ariete signo mobili orientali calido et sicco igneo colerico et masculinis atque appetibili ; bonum est iter versus orientem incipere et in illam partem ad mercandum ire
msItem.explicit: 119r pedes et omnes partes eorum et quicquid fit de igne uel cum igne , Tempus dat aquosum frigidi et humidum

note.p: This text is largely concerned with the influence of the moon in conjunction with the various signs of the zodiac: there is a section for the moon in combination with each zodiac sign, starting with Aries, but the section for Aquarius seems to have been omitted from this copy of the text.

It is possible that this text belongs with the previous text beginning 'Quicumque cursum lune scire desiderat ...' on f. 104v; a similar text can be found in Cambridge, University Library, MS Add. 6860, ff. 77v-80r, with the rubric 'canones lune' and with the opening 'QVicumque cursum lune scire voluerit . sciat primo quomodo sol per signa vadit . Sol namque in quolibet anno pertransit omnia signa ...', but the CUL MS Add. 6860 text diverges from the MS O.1.77 text after the first sentence. The text in MS O.1.77, although apparently deficient, seems to have been originally copied with a longer preface than the version in CUL MS Add. 6860 as the two texts converge once again and follow each other closely at Trinity College, MS O.1.77, f. 109r line 5, 'CVm luna fuerit in ariete signo mobili orientali calido et sicco igneo colerico et masculinis atque appetibili ; bonum est iter versus orientem incipere ...' and CUL MS Add. 6860, f. 78r, line 8, 'CVm luna fuerit in arriete signo firmo orientali calido et sic igneo colerico et masculo bonunm est iter versus orientem incipere ...'. The two manuscripts are aligned thereafter, with further paragraphs on the influence of the moon in each sign of the zodiac, although MS O.1.77 omits the paragraph on the influence of the moon in Aquarius. The text in CUL MS Add. 6860, f. 80r ends (ll. 6-7) 'pedes et omnes eorum partes et quicquid fit cum igne uel de igne vis facere . Tempus dat aquosum frigidum et humidum . Explicit'

Similar text (without possible preface Trinity College MS O.1.77, ff. 104v-109r) in Vatican City, Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana, MS Urb. Lat. 1398, ff. 23r-24v ; in BAV MS Urb. Lat. 1398 the text has the title 'Incipit tractatus de operationibus lune secundum disposicionem signorum'.

Other similar texts: Erfurt, Universitätsbibliothek Erfurt, Dep. Erf., CA 4° 385, ff. 159r-162r, and London, Wellcome Library, MS 537, ff. 318v-319v, the Wellcome manuscript and Trinity MS O.1.77 diverge at the end of Trinity MS O.1.77 f. 105v.

msItem.title: Note on the influences of the planets

note.p:
Full transcription of the note on the influence of the planets on f. 200v:
The course of þe planete Saturne is on sonday . and he regneþ ouer þe spele and þe lyver , The course of þe planete Iubiter is on monday . and he regneþ ouer þe mylte , The course of mars is on twisday . and he regneþ ouer þe galle , The course of þe Sonne is on wendisday and he regneþ ouer þe herte ouer þe l The course of þe planete Venus is on þursday and he regneth ouer þe lunges , The course of mercury is on fryday . he regneþ ouer þe mydryf and þe galle , The course of þe mone is on saturday . he ouer þe stomake and þe guttes ;

foliation.p: Foliation in use in this record produced for the Curious Cures in Cambridge Libraries Project: ?16th century foliation sequence for core leaves with later additions and corrections, particularly of endleaves.
foliation.note:
The majority of the core leaves are foliated in ink as ff. 1-27 29-138 138-169 169-170 170-173 (for ff. 1-27 29-138 138a-173) in a ?16th century hand in the upper outer corner of each recto. The ink foliation sequence was continued by a pencil foliator who added the remaining designations ff. 174-202 to the upper outer corner of the remaining rectos. Another pencil foliator correctedthe duplicate designations in the ink foliation by adding a postpositive 'a' to the second of the duplicate designations (i.e., ff. 138a, 169a and 170a).
The folio designations of the core leaves (ff. 1-202) follow the designations written on the upper outer corner of each recto, including the use of ff. 138a, 169a, and 170a to differentiate between duplicate designations. The designation f. 28 is skipped in this record following the accidental omission of this designation by the ink foliator
The medieval parchment endleaves have the designations ff. [i] - [iii] in this record
The early modern paper endleaves have the designations ff. [a]=[b] and [c]-[d]

collation.p: A small, tightly bound volume arranged as described below. The volume has been conserved, and all quires have been taken down and remounted on guardstrips at an unknown time; these guard strips are visible at the boundaries between the quires. Folios [i] and [ii] are parchment, and [iii] is paper. Quires 1-25 are paper, and Quire 26 is parchment.

A quire has almost certainly been lost between the present Quires 13 and 14 (i.e., between the present ff. 105v and f. 106r) as the medieval alphanumeric leaf sequences are disrupted at the boundary between these quires; there are two medieval alphanumeric leaf sequences in this volume, the first (cancelled) sequence jumps from 'S' (Quire 13) to 'V' (Quire 14) omitting 'T', and the second sequence jumps from 'n' (Quire 13) to 'p' (Quire 14) omitting 'o'. In addition, the catchwords at the bottom of f. 105v ('a sole vte folium') do not match the opening words of f. 106r, 'in kalendario'.

signatures.p:
Two sets of medieval alphanumeric leaf signatures (letter + roman numeral, i.e, ai-aiiij, bi-biiij etc) present in the lower outer corner of the rectos in the the first half of most quires, both sequences appear to have been added by the same scribe. Most of the signatures in the first sequence have been cancelled by being struck out, but are still legible. Some designations undoubtedly lost due to trimming. Probably one quire lost between Quires 13 and 14 (see Collation). The remaining designations for the two sequences are as follows:

catchwords.seg: Catchwords present in the lower inner corner of the last verso of most quires. Most catchwords are enclosed in a simple rectangular frame and some have been partially damaged due to trimming.

supportDesc.condition: In fair condition. Some leaves partially damaged due to liquids. Some marginal annotations and catchwords damaged or lost due to later trimming, see e.g., catchword 'membra' on f. 166v. Some marginal flourishes attached to decorative initials lost to later trimming, see e.g., f. 101v.

layout.seg: Folios [ii] recto - [iii] recto informally written with no visible ruling, typically 18 lines to the page.

Folios 1r-202v: Ruled in leadpoint and drypoint (drypoint possibly transferred impression from leadpoint ruling), frame only. Written in single-column format, typically 14 lines to the page and written mostly below top line (see e.g., f. 124r, drypoint ruled), but occasionally above top line (see e.g., f. 98r, drypoint ruled).

handNote.p: Main-text spaces of folios 1r-199v written in anglicana by Honkapohja 'Hand A'. Honkapohja summarised previous comments on this scribe and noted that M.R. James describes the work of this scribe as 'roughly written', and Voigts described the hand as 'pointed'. Honkapohja also believes this scribe to be responsible for the rubrics written in a more formal grade of anglicana throughout the volume. See Honkapohja (2013) for a detailed analysis of this scribe's work in this manuscript.

'Hand A' uses single- and double-compartment a, looped ascenders on b, d, h, and l and multiple forms of s. The letter h has an elongated 'leg' or second minim that drops well below the baseline. The letter y has a long diagonal descender with a tail that terminates with a flick to the right.

handNote.p: Middle English and macronic texts on ff. [ii] recto, [ii] verso, [iii] recto and 200v all written in anglicana; Mooney suggests these three texts may be the work of the same scribe. This scribe is Honkapohja 'Hand B'. Honkapohja also identified this hand in the marginal annotation on f. 127v. See Honkapohja (2013) for a detailed analysis of this scribe's work in this manuscript. Honkapohja states that the letterforms of Hands A and B are 'very similar', but also notes that one distinguishing feature is that 'Hand B uses the kidney-shaped s in word-final position, which is never used by Hand A'.

decoNote.p: Folios 24v-27r: the 'Twenty Jordans' illustrated sequence of urine flask diagnostic indications.
Folio 178v: simple diagram of a ?distillation flask in the outer margin
Folio 95v: a 'Zodiac Man' diagram, the man rendered in text-ink and the zodiac labels written in red.

Folio 1r: Large puzzle initial 'O'(mne) in red blue and taupe (perhaps faded folium) with marginal flourishing extended into a full page frame. Smaller flourished initials, typically blue initials in the 'Lombardic' style 2-3 lines high with red internal and marginal flourishing and occasional taupe (perhaps faded folium) flourishes throughout at the major and minor divisions of the texts.

Rubrication throughout at the major and minor divisions of the texts generally by underlining headings and sub-headings in red. Minor divisions within the texts also indiciated by touching the first initial with red.
Guide letters in dark ink occasionally present within the matrix of a decorative initial, see e.g., f. 97v, 'Pisces' with a small guide letter 'p' visible within the decorative letter 'P'.

note.p: Two former classmarks in ink in different hands on f. i recto 'L.3' and '3.7.4'.

A name in ink on f. i recto in a 16th century hand, the first name 'John' easily legible, the second name partially erased, but readable as 'Brownin' (for ?Browning) under UV, perhaps the name of a former owner. A number 'xxii' below, perhaps in the same hand.
Trinity College Library stamp in ink on f. i recto.

binding.p: Quarter-bound in ?tawed skin with paper sides over paste- or mill-boards. No raised bands on spine. Spine capped at head and tail by back-material, no headbands visible.
Paper pastedowns at each end of the volume. The inside front cover contains the present shelfmark 'O.7.37' written in pencil and a Trinity College armorial bookplate.

Two post-medieval paper endleaves, ff. [a]-[b] at the front of the volume and two postmedieval paper endleaves at the rear of the volume, f. [c]-[d] at the rear of the volume; all post-medieval paper endleaves probably contemporary with the binding and all blank.
Dimensions (L x W x H): 110 x 75 x 45 mm

Traces of a former binding (probably the original 15th-century binding) present in oxidation stains on ff. [i] and ff. 201-202. The original binding of MS O.1.77 probably included a strap-and-pin closure, which was not a particularly fashionable style of book-fastening in 15th-century England, but may have been necessary for this volume due to its unusual proportions. There is a small round hole in the centre of both ff. 201-202, and the edge of the hole is stained green - this is indicative of a brass pin plate having been mounted at the centre of the rear board of the former binding. There is a small abrasion stained green and a slightly rectanglar impresion in the parchment directly under the '77' on f. [i] recto indicative of a strap with a metal enclosure mounted in the centre of the fore edge of the former front board. The traces of the strap and the pin plate are aligned across the volume.

origin.p: Date of production assigned based on palaeographical features. The volume almost certainly existed in or before 1459/1460 as 'Scribe B' added an astrological calculation for the year 1459 to the margin of f. 127v and another calculation for 1460 to f. 200r. Place of production assigned based on palaeographical features and relation of the volume to others in the so-called Voigts-Sloane Group. See A. Honkapohja, esp. pp. 43-46 for further information.

provenance.p: Perhaps owned by John Dee Dee, John, 1527-1608 (b. 1527, d. 1608), English mathematician and court astronomer at the court of Queen Elizabeth I. Dee was a prolific collector of manuscripts and printed books and amassed a substantial personal library in his lifetime. A mark in ink on f. [i] recto (above and to the left of 'L. 3') strongly resembles a mark identified by M.R. James in Cambridge, Trinity College, MS O.8.5, front flyleaf 5r as a 'monogram, seemingly JD'. Roberts and Watson reject James' identification of the monogram, but suggest that the occasional marginal annotations (found particularly in the latter half of the volume) may be in Dee's hand. The mark warrants further investigation. This volume does not appear to be one of the unidentified volumes listed in Dee's Library Catalogue (Cambridge, Trinity College, MS O.4.20 and printed as an annotated facsimile by Roberts and Watson, but Roberts and Watson identify more than 160 manuscripts owned by Dee and not included in the MS O.4.20 catalogue, so absence from that catalogue cannot be relied upon to (dis)prove ownership.
